ole of the Vice-President\n\nThe Vice-President is the second-highest executive officer in Zambia, appointed by the President. They assume the President's duties if the President is incapacitated or during impeachment proceedings. The Vice-President presides over Cabinet meetings in the President's absence and serves as the Leader of Government Business in the National Assembly, signifying the President's recommendations [Data: Entities (41); Relationships (29, 189, 141, 374, 269, +more)].\n\n## Cabinet's advisory and policy-making role\n\nThe Cabinet, comprising high-ranking government officials, advises the President and formulates government policies. It holds the authority to investigate the President's capacity and propose motions for removal if necessary. The Cabinet's decisions are implemented by Permanent Secretaries, ensuring effective governance and administration [Data: Entities (76); Relationships (203, 168, 285, 455, 456, +more)].\n\n## Judicial appointments and oversight\n\nThe President plays a crucial role in the judicial system by appointing judges to the Supreme Court and High Court, with appointments requiring ratification by the National Assembly. The President can also appoint tribunals to investigate the removal of judges, ensuring oversight and accountability within the judiciary [Data: Relationships (224, 229, 207, 198, 206, +more)].\"\r\n\n\n-----Entities-----\nhuman_readable_id,title,description,degree\r\n14,REPUBLIC,\"The Republic refers to the nation-state of Zambia. It is governed by the President, the Cabinet, and the National Assembly. The Republic of Zambia is mentioned in the context of legal provisions during wartime or emergencies, including labor requirements. Financial matters, such as public debt, revenues, and expenditures, are managed and audited according to specific articles and regulations. The general revenues and financial procedures of Zambia are discussed in legal documents, highlighting the structured approach to finan